WEBVTT

00:01.001 --> 00:02.836
ANDY: <i>Previously on </i>NYPD Blue.

00:02.919 --> 00:04.421
Lieutenant Rodriguez, Maria Oliveira.

00:04.546 --> 00:06.798
Why wasn't I notified before my mother
was taken to the hospital?

00:07.007 --> 00:08.717
It's Hector Acevedo.
I know she's your mother,

00:08.925 --> 00:10.927
but this is my case.
I can't let you look for him alone.

00:11.803 --> 00:15.515
Did you break in on my mother,
or are you a dead man? Go to the car!

00:15.765 --> 00:17.559
-I'm staying here.
-Go to the car!

00:17.684 --> 00:19.769
You received two complaints,
for excessive force

00:19.853 --> 00:22.397
-when you were in narcotics, right?
-You're in the field as much as I was,

00:22.480 --> 00:24.566
you ruffle a few feathers,
it goes with the territory.

00:24.774 --> 00:26.651
Another complaint
when you were in uniform.

00:27.068 --> 00:30.113
-Goes with the territory, right?
-I was never disciplined for anything,

00:30.196 --> 00:32.323
and I'd put my record up
against any cops.

00:43.501 --> 00:45.879
Mr. Acevedo,
where do you presently reside?

00:45.962 --> 00:47.547
Green Haven Correctional Facility.

00:47.756 --> 00:51.051
-And what are you incarcerated for?
-Burglary, robbery, assault.

00:51.426 --> 00:54.971
-And who was the arresting officer?
-Anthony Rodriguez.

00:55.263 --> 00:57.390
JAMES: Could you describe
the circumstances of that arrest?

00:57.557 --> 01:01.019
Yeah, he busted into my apartment,
he accused me of breaking in on his mom.

01:01.269 --> 01:03.605
-And what happened then?
-He stuck a gun in my face,

01:03.688 --> 01:05.690
said if I didn't confess,
that I'd be a dead man.

01:05.982 --> 01:08.693
-Did you confess at that time?
-As fast as I could.

01:09.235 --> 01:11.571
That wasn't your first contact
with Lieutenant Rodriguez, was it?

01:11.988 --> 01:16.701
No, he arrested me in '93
for selling crack. I served eight years.

01:16.826 --> 01:19.204
JAMES: Mr. Acevedo, were you guilty
of all the crimes

01:19.329 --> 01:21.039
-you've been convicted of?
-Yes, I was.

01:21.289 --> 01:23.833
Lieutenant Rodriguez
put you in jail twice.

01:24.042 --> 01:28.254
Can you see why your testimony here today
might be viewed with some skepticism?

01:28.505 --> 01:30.215
Look, I'm paying for what I did.

01:30.673 --> 01:31.674
And I'm owning up.

01:31.758 --> 01:34.219
And what I'm saying happened,
really happened, okay.

01:34.677 --> 01:37.013
Whatever bad things I've done in my life,
I'm sorry.

01:37.097 --> 01:40.642
A cop shoving a gun in my face,
in my house, that's wrong too.

01:40.892 --> 01:42.936
Thank you. No further questions.

01:43.478 --> 01:44.562
JUDGE: Your witness.

01:45.647 --> 01:47.232
Mr. Acevedo...

01:48.900 --> 01:51.361
you say you confessed
because Lieutenant Rodriguez

01:51.486 --> 01:53.655
-threatened to kill you, correct?
-That's right.

01:53.988 --> 01:55.824
Did you challenge
that confession in court?

01:55.907 --> 01:56.991
No.

01:57.200 --> 01:59.285
Let's talk about
why you're testifying now.

01:59.619 --> 02:01.579
-Were you subpoenaed to appear?
-No.

02:01.788 --> 02:04.332
-Then how'd you come to be here?
-I read about the case.

02:05.125 --> 02:06.751
I wrote a letter to Mr. Sinclair,

02:06.835 --> 02:09.379
and I said I had information
that he might find useful.

02:09.712 --> 02:13.007
So, you're here out of your devotion
to the legal process?

02:13.258 --> 02:15.135
-Objection.
-Withdrawn.

02:15.927 --> 02:18.847
Any chance you might be harboring
a little ill will?

02:19.097 --> 02:22.142
Nothing that would make me
lie in this court today.

02:22.267 --> 02:26.229
Of course not. Convictions
for drug dealing, robbery, assault.

02:26.396 --> 02:28.815
Lying's not consistent
with that moral code.

02:28.982 --> 02:30.775
-Objection.
-JUDGE: Sustained.

02:31.860 --> 02:34.696
-Nothing further.
-You can step down, Mr. Acevedo.

02:35.113 --> 02:37.031
Call your next witness, Mr. Sinclair.

02:37.782 --> 02:40.368
The defense calls
Detective Maria Olivera.

02:42.620 --> 02:44.706
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

02:47.750 --> 02:49.752
-Sidebar, Your Honor.
-Approach.

02:57.552 --> 02:59.804
The prosecution requests an offer of proof

02:59.888 --> 03:02.223
as to the substance
of this witness's testimony.

03:02.640 --> 03:06.603
Detective Oliveira was in the room
with Lieutenant Rodriguez and Mr. Acevedo.

03:06.686 --> 03:08.021
She's a corroborating witness.

03:08.354 --> 03:10.940
Judge, the jury has already heard
from Mr. Acevedo.

03:11.024 --> 03:13.318
The detective will be offering
cumulative testimony

03:13.401 --> 03:14.527
on a collateral matter.

03:15.528 --> 03:19.449
The impeachment of Lieutenant Rodriguez
is hardly collateral.

03:20.658 --> 03:21.910
I'll allow it.

03:22.660 --> 03:25.246
I have a matter in another case,
so we'll take a brief recess.

03:25.496 --> 03:27.624
That should give you time
to get up to speed, Miss Heywood.

03:27.832 --> 03:29.125
Thank you, Your Honor.

03:29.876 --> 03:33.296
Court is adjourned until 11:30.
Take the jury out, Eddie.

03:36.299 --> 03:38.176
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

03:39.594 --> 03:40.637
What's up?

03:41.679 --> 03:44.349
You never said anything
about another detective being there

03:44.432 --> 03:45.475
for the Acevedo arrest.

03:45.683 --> 03:47.435
Oliveira, I didn't see
any reason to jam her up.

03:47.685 --> 03:50.188
She's jammed up, Tony.
She's been called to testify.

03:50.438 --> 03:54.150
She's not gonna corroborate Acevedo.
She's a stand-up cop, and there's no way.

03:54.234 --> 03:55.902
I don't want to hear
about how you think she'll lie

03:56.027 --> 03:59.781
to cover your ass because I hope you know
how bad a position that would put me in.

04:00.490 --> 04:02.784
I'm just telling you,
if she corroborates that witness,

04:02.867 --> 04:05.036
you'll look like a violent cop
who's quick to pull his gun,

04:05.119 --> 04:08.164
and I'll look like I'm prosecuting a guy
who acted in self-defense.

04:10.583 --> 04:11.626
I gotta go.

04:16.965 --> 04:19.133
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

05:18.318 --> 05:19.694
(MUSIC CONCLUDES)

05:26.617 --> 05:28.286
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

05:30.079 --> 05:31.122
Woah!

05:32.248 --> 05:34.417
-He going out of the picture?
-Fifty-fifty.

05:34.751 --> 05:37.211
Ron Szudarek. Stomped, cigarette burns.

05:37.462 --> 05:39.464
-They did a number on him.
-The victim say anything?

05:39.547 --> 05:41.007
He had all he could do to moan.

05:41.466 --> 05:43.968
Neighbor down the hall called it in.
Dan Spolen.

05:44.218 --> 05:46.262
-He said he didn't hear any beating.
-You talk to him?

05:46.429 --> 05:47.805
No, not yet. He's all yours.

05:47.930 --> 05:51.017
-(SIRENS BLARING)
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER OVER RADIO)

05:51.392 --> 05:53.227
ANDY: (CLEARS THROAT) Mr. Spolen...

05:54.812 --> 05:57.523
-The wife, she's terrified.
-Sure.

05:58.024 --> 06:00.568
How well do you know Mr. Szudarek?

06:00.651 --> 06:03.071
I wish better,
but he's not a real neighborly type.

06:03.279 --> 06:04.614
How'd you come across him this morning?

06:04.864 --> 06:07.700
I was heading up
to read the paper on the roof.

06:07.784 --> 06:11.412
I have an outdoor set up there.
Chairs, umbrella.

06:11.788 --> 06:15.291
And I noticed his door was open,
so I knock, and I found him on the floor.

06:16.834 --> 06:18.544
-That's your apartment?
-Hmm.

06:20.755 --> 06:22.298
How did you see that the door was open?

06:25.968 --> 06:27.220
Just... did.

06:29.097 --> 06:30.598
Why did the color just drain
out of your face?

06:32.141 --> 06:35.186
I was going to the roof
to smoke a cigarette.

06:36.104 --> 06:38.106
I'm not supposed to,
but once in a while...

06:38.189 --> 06:39.899
That doesn't explain what
you're doing down there.

06:40.608 --> 06:44.779
I keep the cigarettes in there,
and mouthwash, and hand sanitizer.

06:47.448 --> 06:49.534
If we could just keep this between us.

06:51.494 --> 06:52.370
(SIGHS)

06:57.959 --> 06:58.960
(GASPS)

07:02.296 --> 07:03.339
FEMALE VOICE: Great.

07:05.633 --> 07:07.176
I am in for a ration of hell.

07:07.552 --> 07:10.555
Remind her how your neighbor's face
got turned to ground chuck.

07:10.680 --> 07:13.224
That might take her mind off
your horrible little secret.

07:14.475 --> 07:15.560
Go home.

07:25.778 --> 07:26.821
What's going on?

07:26.946 --> 07:29.240
CONNIE: I guess the defense called
this detective from the 8-3,

07:29.490 --> 07:32.034
-a Maria Oliveira.
-Yeah, I know that name.

07:32.285 --> 07:34.203
When the lieutenant's mom got
assaulted, she caught the case.

07:34.454 --> 07:37.206
She was there when the boss got
the confession off that guy.

07:37.457 --> 07:38.875
-Yeah.
-That ain't good.

07:39.250 --> 07:41.669
And I guess it kind of took Valerie
by surprise.

07:43.296 --> 07:44.797
What do we have on that assault case?

07:44.881 --> 07:46.924
Victim's at Bellevue. He should make it.

07:47.008 --> 07:49.051
Medavoy and Jones are on their way
to interview an employee

07:49.135 --> 07:50.136
at the victim's barber shop.

07:51.846 --> 07:53.890
-Can I help you?
-ANDREA: My name's Andrea Miner,

07:53.973 --> 07:56.642
and I need to talk to someone
about my husband being missing.

07:58.811 --> 08:01.063
Detective Clark,
my partner, Detective Sipowicz.

08:02.398 --> 08:03.858
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

08:04.317 --> 08:06.527
-When did you see your husband last?
-ANDREA: Yesterday morning.

08:06.736 --> 08:09.989
He had an interview at E.N.L.
Moving and Storage to drive a truck,

08:10.072 --> 08:11.657
and I called, but he never showed up.

08:12.074 --> 08:14.619
His name's Troy Miner,

08:15.077 --> 08:17.288
and he's not answering
his pager, his cell.

08:17.371 --> 08:18.915
-ANDY: How old's your husband?
-ANDREA: Thirty.

08:19.665 --> 08:21.959
And, no, there's not some hoe on the side,

08:22.043 --> 08:24.879
and no, he's not in a gang,
and no, he does not have a drug

08:24.962 --> 08:26.839
or an alcohol or a gambling problem.

08:27.215 --> 08:30.051
He's a family man.
And there's definitely something wrong.

08:30.510 --> 08:34.180
Well, seeing as he's an adult,
and it's been less than 48 hours.

08:34.430 --> 08:36.599
-Well, can you just take my word for it?
-I'm just telling you that we can't take

08:36.849 --> 08:38.684
an official missing person's report.

08:38.851 --> 08:41.354
-But we will look into it.
-ANDREA: I'd really appreciate that.

08:43.105 --> 08:46.734
Um, the last number I put on there
is Troy's cousin, Corey Mack.

08:47.068 --> 08:49.862
He's a thug. He may have tried
to mix Troy up in something.

08:50.196 --> 08:51.322
We'll talk to Corey.

08:52.490 --> 08:54.867
-And we're on this, okay?
-Thank you.

09:06.462 --> 09:07.547
GREG: Excuse me. Bob Drazin?

09:08.381 --> 09:09.757
Detectives Medavoy and Jones.

09:10.341 --> 09:12.468
Oh, how you doin'? Any word on Ron?

09:12.885 --> 09:14.011
BALDWIN: Yeah, he's hanging in.

09:14.220 --> 09:16.264
Yeah, I been down at the hospital,
but they won't let me talk to him.

09:16.806 --> 09:18.432
Well, he's still being treated.

09:18.808 --> 09:22.061
So, I came back here to keep busy,
but I can't open up.

09:22.353 --> 09:23.396
It's disrespectful.

09:23.896 --> 09:29.360
-Sure. We got some questions about Ron.
-Good guy. Didn't deserve this.

09:29.610 --> 09:31.153
You know anybody
that would want to hurt him?

09:31.487 --> 09:33.155
No, but whoever did...

09:33.656 --> 09:36.117
-You two close?
-Yeah, knew Ron a long time.

09:36.450 --> 09:38.911
-He got any enemies?
-Everyone liked him.

09:39.078 --> 09:40.246
-He owe money?
-No.

09:40.496 --> 09:42.582
-He got a drug problem?
-Come on, you're totally off.

09:42.790 --> 09:46.294
We're off? This isn't 20 questions, Bob.
What's going on?

09:48.462 --> 09:49.714
I'm sorry.

09:51.299 --> 09:53.676
I was thinking of taking care
of this problem on my own,

09:53.884 --> 09:54.927
and at the same time,

09:55.011 --> 09:56.929
hoping that someone would
come along to stop me.

09:57.138 --> 09:59.682
-You're just not quite getting it.
-Yeah, well, give us a hand.

09:59.890 --> 10:03.227
You want to talk to our landlady,
all right? Doris Vidi.

10:03.769 --> 10:06.063
She upped the rent a couple months ago,
trying to get us out.

10:06.397 --> 10:07.607
How heated did it get?

10:07.773 --> 10:09.233
BOB: Well, there was a lot of yelling
on the phone.

10:09.317 --> 10:10.359
Yeah well, how'd that get to torture?

10:10.651 --> 10:12.194
She's an old hatchet-faced guinea.

10:12.445 --> 10:14.530
She's got a pair of degenerate sons.

10:14.739 --> 10:16.866
They collect every month.
I can see them doing it.

10:16.991 --> 10:18.200
GREG: Anybody else come to mind?

10:18.284 --> 10:20.328
'Cause he was beat worse
than a rent dispute.

10:20.453 --> 10:23.414
No, no. He's... he's a well-liked guy.

10:23.706 --> 10:26.292
Those brothers? Those brothers are trash.

10:26.500 --> 10:29.045
These brothers, this is who you're gonna
pay a visit to if we hadn't come along?

10:29.670 --> 10:31.756
With a bat in my right hand
and a pipe in my left.

10:31.839 --> 10:33.966
Yeah, but you're not going to now,
'cause I'm gonna have to take you in.

10:36.385 --> 10:38.095
Yeah, if I keep busy, I'll be fine.

10:38.429 --> 10:41.599
All right, this, uh,
Doris Vidi's phone number.

10:46.604 --> 10:48.481
JAMES: In your initial interview
with Mr. Acevedo,

10:48.731 --> 10:51.525
which was conducted by yourself
and a fellow detective,

10:51.651 --> 10:53.694
did Mr. Acevedo confess?

10:53.861 --> 10:56.197
-No.
-Why was the interview ended?

10:56.364 --> 10:58.866
It was time to regroup,
so we released Mr. Acevedo.

10:58.949 --> 11:00.034
And how would you characterize

11:00.117 --> 11:02.536
the progress of your investigation
at that point?

11:02.745 --> 11:05.122
We felt we had our guy,
and it was just gonna take some time.

11:05.206 --> 11:08.918
What was Mr. Rodriguez's reaction
when you told him that the main suspect

11:09.001 --> 11:11.545
in the assault on his mother
was walking out the door?

11:13.214 --> 11:15.257
He was a little frustrated,
which was understandable.

11:15.508 --> 11:17.885
When did you see Mr. Acevedo again?

11:18.219 --> 11:20.805
At his apartment in Brooklyn,
later that afternoon.

11:21.430 --> 11:24.016
With whom did you go
to Mr. Acevedo's apartment?

11:24.141 --> 11:25.309
Lieutenant Rodriguez.

11:25.476 --> 11:28.104
How did you gain entry
into Mr. Acevedo's apartment?

11:28.521 --> 11:29.939
We knocked on the door. He let us in.

11:31.857 --> 11:34.026
-He let you in?
-Yes.

11:34.151 --> 11:36.737
At that time, did Mr. Acevedo
confess to the assault

11:36.821 --> 11:39.156
-on Lieutenant Rodriguez's mother?
-Eventually, yes.

11:39.323 --> 11:43.536
Did Lieutenant Rodriguez
threaten Mr. Acevedo's life

11:43.703 --> 11:46.789
-in order to obtain that confession?
-No, he did not.

11:47.665 --> 11:51.043
You didn't hear Lieutenant Rodriguez
tell Mr. Acevedo,

11:51.252 --> 11:53.295
"You're a dead man. I'll kill you,"

11:53.379 --> 11:56.340
all the while with a gun
in Mr. Acevedo's throat?

11:56.424 --> 11:57.800
Objection. Leading.

11:58.050 --> 12:02.430
Your Honor, permission to treat
Detective Oliveira as a hostile witness.

12:02.596 --> 12:04.056
JUDGE: Go ahead, Mr. Sinclair.

12:04.473 --> 12:05.725
The witness can answer.

12:06.392 --> 12:08.227
Lieutenant Rodriguez
never said any of that.

12:08.352 --> 12:11.355
Lieutenant Rodriguez,
who was interviewing a suspect

12:11.647 --> 12:16.360
he believed assaulted his mom,
was what? Calm?

12:16.485 --> 12:17.486
He was professional.

12:17.820 --> 12:21.031
Are you asking us to believe
that Hector Acevedo,

12:21.115 --> 12:22.783
certainly no stranger to the legal system,

12:23.367 --> 12:26.245
suddenly and spontaneously gave it up?

12:26.620 --> 12:29.081
We convinced him a confession
would get him favorable treatment.

12:29.999 --> 12:31.083
Oh, that's all it took.

12:31.292 --> 12:35.129
A common, lame tactic
about favorable treatment

12:35.504 --> 12:38.549
that Mr. Acevedo has doubtless heard
a million times,

12:38.841 --> 12:42.094
and knows firsthand, is not true.

12:42.178 --> 12:45.681
Objection. I don't recall that
testimony from Mr. Acevedo.

12:46.098 --> 12:48.559
-Sustained.
-Detective...

12:50.186 --> 12:52.104
have you ever heard
of the blue wall of silence?

12:52.229 --> 12:54.315
Cops backing up cops,
regardless of the truth?

12:54.607 --> 12:56.108
-Objection.
-I'll allow it.

12:58.486 --> 13:00.154
I've testified to how
it went down, counselor.

13:02.490 --> 13:04.283
If you say so, detective.

13:06.660 --> 13:08.120
No further questions.

13:19.381 --> 13:22.551
-So your cousin Troy, you two were tight.
-Yeah.

13:23.302 --> 13:25.846
His wife Andrea came in,
wanted to report him as missing.

13:26.180 --> 13:27.807
Oh, yeah, she called me about that.

13:28.140 --> 13:31.101
-You heard from him?
-No, I don't know where that fool's at.

13:31.185 --> 13:34.271
Hey, Corey, seeing as we're looking
to help you find your cousin,

13:34.355 --> 13:36.607
and we're not looking to jam
either of the two of you up.

13:37.358 --> 13:41.278
You think it's possible that we could have
a little honest conversation here, Corey?

13:41.445 --> 13:42.655
Oh, absolutely, that's possible.

13:42.905 --> 13:46.450
'Cause we'd rather clear this up with you
before we have to go back to Troy's wife

13:46.575 --> 13:48.953
and ask her questions
maybe she doesn't wanna hear.

13:49.161 --> 13:52.039
-Yeah, that's cool.
-Okay, then, so what's going on?

13:52.373 --> 13:53.749
I don't know where Troy is.

13:54.041 --> 13:56.085
He got fired from his job two months ago.

13:56.168 --> 13:58.921
-COREY: Yeah.
-He got a DWI three months ago.

13:59.004 --> 14:01.048
Yeah, coming back from a birthday party.

14:01.257 --> 14:02.675
That's how he ended up losing his job.

14:02.758 --> 14:04.552
JOHN JR.: So he's got a wife,
two kids at home,

14:04.760 --> 14:06.637
he's out of work
for the first time in his life.

14:07.054 --> 14:09.098
Wouldn't be unheard of for a guy
in that situation

14:09.181 --> 14:11.976
-to lose his way a little.
-Drinking, drugs, leaving town?

14:13.853 --> 14:14.979
Let's hear it, Corey.

14:15.938 --> 14:18.148
Troy... (SIGHS)

14:19.817 --> 14:23.153
He got himself a girl on the side.
My guess, that's where he's at.

14:23.279 --> 14:26.115
-Who's the chick?
-He met her on one of his deliveries.

14:26.615 --> 14:28.659
(LAUGHS HYSTERICALLY)

14:28.868 --> 14:32.913
Oh, sorry, man. You gotta know Troy.
I mean, he has no game at all.

14:32.997 --> 14:35.583
That's why I could see him pulling
a rookie move, like not coming home.

14:35.833 --> 14:39.670
That's real funny and all, Corey,
but we've been spending time on this.

14:39.962 --> 14:42.006
-Oh, no, I got you.
-And Troy's wife,

14:42.172 --> 14:44.758
she's operating under the assumption
that Troy's a family man.

14:45.134 --> 14:48.971
He'll turn up, all right?
He's just out getting some new ass.

14:49.096 --> 14:50.973
If you were married to Andrea,
you would too.

14:51.056 --> 14:52.725
All right, if we don't hear
from him today,

14:52.808 --> 14:54.435
the next time his wife
pushes us for an answer,

14:54.518 --> 14:55.519
She's gonna get one.

14:55.769 --> 14:57.146
All right, just hold off
on that for a minute.

14:57.229 --> 14:58.814
I'll make some phone calls. He'll turn up.

14:59.064 --> 15:00.190
Get on it.

15:05.154 --> 15:07.489
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

15:10.492 --> 15:11.994
TONY: You talk to Szudarek's landlady?

15:12.494 --> 15:15.331
Yeah. Doris Vidi. Battle-ax.

15:16.457 --> 15:19.418
She barely gave us the time of day,
and then she nearly threw a lamp at us

15:19.627 --> 15:21.211
when we asked for a place
to look for her sons.

15:21.337 --> 15:22.296
Her sons?

15:22.379 --> 15:24.924
Yeah, who Szudarek's employee
thinks did the dirty work.

15:25.174 --> 15:27.801
They both got records for assault,
but no answer at either apartments.

15:29.345 --> 15:31.931
The hospital. Szudarek's awake,
apparently lucid.

